# Cursor Governance Wiring Boundary

## Two distinct planes

| Plane | Path | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| Governance reference plane | `.cursor-commands -> $HOME/.cursor-governance` | Commands, skills, scripts, canonical documents, and explicit rule references |
| Cursor rule activation plane | `.cursor/rules/` | Cursor-native project discovery, repository rules, subtree rules, and selected shared rule files |

`.cursor-commands` does not replace Cursor-native project-rule discovery.

## Repository path contracts

- `.cursor-commands` is the sole workspace symlink to the governance root.
- `.cursor/governance/` is a real local directory.
- `.cursor/governance/CANONICAL_LAW.md` is a file symlink to the canonical law.
- `.cursor/rules/` is a real repository-owned directory and must never be replaced by a whole-directory global-rules symlink.
- Shared rules may be projected only as selected individual file symlinks under an explicit fail-closed selection policy.
- `.cursor/commands` and `.cursor/skills` remain forbidden duplicates of the shared entry point.

## Mutation rule

Wiring tools must preserve repository-owned directories. Unexpected symlinks, files, and filename collisions fail closed instead of being renamed or overwritten by assumption.
